st common household expense categories -- tCross-national and comparative perspectives -- tThe Slovenian experience with three methods for defining the minimum income -- tApplying the Minimum Income Standard in diverse national contexts -- tThe steep and winding road to comparable reference budgets in Europe -- tAdequate income in Portugal: a comparison of two estimation methods -- tPolicy and practice -- tBasic needs budgets in policy and practice -- tEstablishing a national standard: the role of the UK’s Minimum Income Standard in policy and practice -- tMinimum Income Standards in the Basic Income debate -- tConclusions -- tMinimum income standards and reference budgets: past, present, future? -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aResearch into minimum income standards and reference budgets around the world is compared in this illuminating collection from leading academics in the field. From countries with long established research traditions to places where it is relatively new, contributors set out the different aims and objectives of investigations into the minimum needs and requirements of populations, and the historical contexts, theoretical frameworks and methodological issues that lie behind each approach. For policymakers, practitioners and social policy and poverty academics, this essential review of learnings to date and future prospects for research is all the more relevant in light of the COVID-19 pandemic, testing health and social protection systems around the globe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh1 aAalto, Kristiina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAbe, Aya K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela